# RTL `flex-col` Alignment

In a `flex-col` container with `dir="rtl"` (or RTL writing mode), the **cross axis follows the inline direction**, so `align-items` values are physically reversed:

| Class | LTR result | RTL result |
|-------|-----------|-----------|
| `items-start` | physical LEFT | **physical RIGHT ✓** |
| `items-end` | physical RIGHT | **physical LEFT ✗** |

## Rule

To right-align children in an RTL `flex-col` → use **`items-start`**  
To left-align children in an RTL `flex-col` → use **`items-end`**

```jsx
{/* ❌ WRONG — looks right-aligned in LTR, but left-aligned in RTL */}
<div className="flex flex-col items-end" dir="rtl">
  <p>שאלות ותשובות</p>
</div>

{/* ✅ CORRECT — right-aligned in RTL */}
<div className="flex flex-col items-start" dir="rtl">
  <p>שאלות ותשובות</p>
</div>
```

## RTL `flex-row`: DOM order = visual position

In `flex-row` with RTL, the **first DOM child appears on the physical right**. Never use `flex-row-reverse` to fake RTL — reorder elements in JSX instead.

```jsx
{/* RTL row: icon renders on the LEFT, text on the RIGHT (correct) */}
<div className="flex flex-row gap-3" dir="rtl">
  <p className="flex-1 text-right">question text</p>  {/* → physical right */}
  <div>icon</div>                                      {/* → physical left */}
</div>
```
